Creating classes supports Object Oriented Programming because classes let you group data and functions that belong together into one object. This helps model real world things in code and makes programs easier to reuse and organize. For example, a BankAccount class could store the balance and include functions like deposit() and withdraw().

Classes also help follow SOLID design principles by keeping code clean and structured. For example, the Single Responsibility Principle means a class should only have one job, like a LoginSystem class that only handles user authentication. This makes the program easier to maintain and extend later without breaking other parts of the code.
